@fullyallocated @symmtry69 Yeah! That's what I said in response to Brian's reply too

@joey_debruin @fullyallocated Oooh great point! Yeah I think platforms should be data opt-in, almost like @useGALLERY style for NFT collections.

Passive models (i.e. inclusion of data w/o user say) makes more sense for community-wide model benchmarking rather than interpretations at the individual level

@joey_debruin @fullyallocated Right. Yeah there's probably some happy medium between the illusion of "any contributor is a good contributor" and the extremes of dot collector systems at Bridgewater. 

I'm kind of working through an education based leveling system, so maybe we can debate on that example later!

@joey_debruin @fullyallocated Exactly, so if the community is taking the risk then the penalty should fall on the applicant/contributor for the most part. Like if a bounty is unfinished, or a proposal has a negative effect. 

These are all good questions, maybe we need to run a Twitter spaces on this lol
@Flynnjamm @fullyallocated The benchmark continues to shift at a different rate, so in effect you've "lost" levels.

@Flynnjamm @fullyallocated I mean depends on the design around. Say you're either moving up or down levels, that doesn't have to mean your access/status has to move with it. 

Also could design it as a level inflation system, which makes sense for something domain specific. So your level goes up only but

@symmtry69 @fullyallocated Token heuristics are too strong for both designers and users, I think negative implies "removed" from a wallet. versus "temporary/natural loss" the way video game SR ranking is interpreted. 

So the mechanisms and marketing around it starts off inherently biased to positive only
@fullyallocated 100%. I think twitch polls/bets are a fun example to build off of as well. Like you could enhance all these forum policy discussions so much with pos/neg gamification
@fullyallocated Most (all?) are missing some element of risk taking. Bearish on positive only reputation systems

Hopefully, this brain dump on web3 data was helpful! If you want to support this work, feel free to collect an entry edition or one of the 100 "Data Landscape" editions ğŸ’˜

Special thanks to @VirtualElena for reviewing and making suggestions as always!

wagmi ğŸ§™

On teams, I cover three of the skill pillars I've seen most prominently in the space. I plan on making this prettier and coming out with content/cohorts across these pillars later on this year - but there should be enough material in this section to get anyone started! https://t.co/utdvZXhI2q

On tools, I cover the web3 data stack, when to use each sub-category, and key communities to get involved in (with people to contact). 

If you've used most of these and are collaborating in some of the key communities, you're a certified web3 analyst to me! https://t.co/YvMCdcV2t4

On thinking, you'll need to understand that open data now means "open data pipeline" rather than "here's some CSVs for u". This changes the flow of work and roles.

I walk through some technical examples of this flow, including a Uniswap proposal @alex_kroeger made last year! https://t.co/yLlwtLtsPn

âœ¨ğŸ“ŠMy inaugural guide to web3 data is here!

> how and why web3 vs web2 data thinking is different
> layers and players of the data landscape, and key communities
> 3 types of data roles with skills mapped out
